Hi @Tom,
I&#39;ll try to respond inline here:
&quot;1. Would you generally use custom controllers with custom view models for the overall layout of the page etc and then when dealing with gets and posts have to use surface controllers? &quot;
This depends on what you are trying to achieve. I think a standard Umbraco developer will probably not worry about their own controllers and views and just use what is created in Umbraco. However, MVC devs that want to do everything in full MVC, i would suggest you create a Hijacked route controller for each doc type you want to render, then just like a regular MVC application, create whatever models and views you require. Your views will then do no querying and your controller will do all queries which can be done by the UmbracoHelper in the controller. As for GETS, this is already handled by hijacked routes, for POSTs like posting for information it is much easier to use SurfaceControllers as they give you all of the underlying methods like return CurrentUmbracoPage() etc... however you can post to whatever controller you like but you&#39;ll then have to redirect to some other page or show a custom template, SurfaceControllers have native support for integrating this stuff into the routing pipeline.
&quot;2. Can a conventional controller that has hijacked a route handle the gets and posts or does it have to be done with partial views and surface controllers? &quot;
Sure, but you&#39;ll have to manually construct your route for BeginForm and wont be able to use BeginUmbracoForm plus the based RenderMvcController doesn&#39;t have all of the built in methods that SurfaceController&#39;s have like RedirectToCurrentUmbracoPage(), etc.. (however, it should so i will add these methods). Again, you can post wherever you like, you can do anything that you can do in normal MVC but if using things like SurfaceController&#39;s will be easier in many cases.
&quot;3. If you wanted to make use of the new 4.5 API controllers etc would the best way be to custom route and then add to umbracos reserved urls? &quot;
Correct, but in 4.11 you won&#39;t have to add the reserved URLs (in most cases) as simple routes in the route table will be added to the reserved paths automatically.
&quot;Just wondering if you had a scenario where you wanted to pass a custom ViewModel down into a partial for use would you need to assign that partial view to the ViewBag as described here: our.umbraco.org/.../30706-Passing-Models-to-Partial-Views &quot;
I&#39;m not really sure what this means, you can easily render a PartialView with your own model just like normal: @Html.Partial(&quot;myPartial&quot;, new MyModel()) If however you want to have things like @Umbraco, etc... in your partial view then you just need to inherit from the correct class. You don&#39;t need to do anything with TempData or anything. All the docs for this are here:
http://our.umbraco.org/documentation/reference/mvc/partial-views/
Here&#39;s the full MVC reference:
http://our.umbraco.org/documentation/Reference/Mvc/

