@Hi Tom,

If you are hijacking a route, you can return any model that you want, however if you are using the standard view generated by Umbraco, you&#39;d have to change this as it expects a type of RenderModel as the model, so change your view to;
@inherits Umbraco.Web.Mvc.UmbracoViewPage&lt;PeopleListViewModel&gt;
Since its a custom model you can&#39;t just do:
return base.Index(yourCustomModel) 
because yourCustomModel is not RenderModel, instead you will have to do get the current view name from the route data, just like we are doing in the base.Index method (you can see this in the source):

var template = ControllerContext.RouteData.Values[&quot;action&quot;].ToString();
if (!EnsurePhsyicalViewExists(template))
{
return Content(&quot;&quot;);
}
return View(template, yourCustomModel);

I will create a new method in the RenderMvcController to make this process easier with a method to get the view name from the route values.

If you have a custom model then you would only inherit from RenderModel if you want the things that are on RenderModel, otherwise you&#39;d just use your own custom model. Inheriting from RenderModel doesn&#39;t give you &#39;access to the cms&#39;, its just a model.

Then when you are rendering your partials, yes you just do this for your partials:

@inherits Umbraco.Web.Mvc.UmbracoViewPage&lt;PersonViewModel&gt;

and to render just do:

@foreach(var person in Model.People)
{
@Html.Partial(&quot;myPartial&quot;, person)
}

