Hi @Ed,

I&#39;m not really sure I understand what you are trying to explain with your code above. However, I can tell you how to use a layout page, this is very easy:

I can create a _Layout.cshtml page that I can reuse for my templates and have access to the UmbracoHelper, RenderModel, etc... by just inheriting from the correct view, as an example, here&#39;s a _Layout.cshtml page:

@inherits Umbraco.Web.Mvc.UmbracoTemplatePage
@{
    Layout = null;
}

&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
&lt;html&gt;
&lt;head&gt;
	&lt;title&gt;@Model.Content.Name&lt;/title&gt;
&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body&gt;
    &lt;h1&gt;@Model.Content.Name&lt;/h1&gt;

    @RenderBody()
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;

Then i might have another view called &quot;Home.cshtml&quot; that uses this template:

@inherits Umbraco.Web.Mvc.UmbracoTemplatePage
@{	
    Layout = &quot;_Layout.cshtml&quot;;	
}

&lt;p&gt;
  Hello world, this is my home page, it was last updated on this date: @Model.Content.UpdateDate
&lt;/p&gt;

This is no different to normal MVC, but if you want access to the Umbraco stuff in your layout page, you&#39;d need to have it inherit from Umbraco.Web.Mvc.UmbracoTemplatePage as seen above. That is of course if you are passing an instance of &#39;RenderModel&#39; to your views.

