@Carl: the Model for an Umbraco page is the &#39;content&#39; node, so you can&#39;t theoretically change the model (though we will be offering support to do this soon... but don&#39;t think this is really what you want). 
So, I&#39;m assuming you&#39;ve made a Surface controller and are posting some data to one of your actions. If your POST is successful, you shouldn&#39;t just return a response, you should redirect to a page so you can avoid the aweful issue of having a user press refresh and have it resubmit the POST. If you POST is not successful, you should return CurrentUmbracoPage, otherwise do a return RedirectToCurrentUmbracoPage. If you do a redirect, you can store your own data inside of TempData to be retrieved in your view. If you don&#39;t do a redirect, you can store your own data inside of the ViewData/ViewBag to be retrieved in your view.
Just FYI, when you POST to a SurfaceController, you are just posting to your own controller which is outside of the Umbraco process, it is just a very normal MVC post. So when you do a return CurrentUmbracoPage call, that then passes execution back to Umbraco to go lookup the page that was posted from and renders it. You could in theory just return your own View(model) which will be completely outside the umbraco process, because it is just an MVC normal controller.

